# duplicate-api-types.allowlist
#
# Phase 0.7 PR2 Class D (TYPEDUP) — pre-existing type duplicates between
# @signacare/shared and apps/web/src/features/*/types/*.ts that the guard
# would otherwise flag. Each entry is one type name per line.
#
# The rule: frontend `types/*.ts` files may only declare types that are
# strictly frontend-only (UI state, form field types, component prop
# types). Any type that represents an API request or response shape must
# live in @signacare/shared and be imported.
#
# Every entry below is a type that is declared in BOTH shared and a
# frontend types/*.ts, with materially different field shapes (i.e. the
# frontend version has drifted from the shared version over time). Each
# one requires per-case investigation:
#
#   1. Which side is correct? Trace the backend service that populates
#      the response to see what field names it really emits.
#   2. Fix the side that's wrong. If the backend is the offender, rename
#      its response fields. If the frontend is the offender, align its
#      schema to the backend reality. Document the real shipped bug in
#      a fix-registry row (`TYPEDUP:<TypeName>`).
#   3. Delete the frontend duplicate and import from `@signacare/shared`.
#   4. Remove the type name from this allowlist.
#
# Adding NEW entries to this file is NOT allowed. The CI guard
# `check-no-duplicate-api-types.sh` uses this file as a grandfather list;
# any new frontend declaration of a shared type name fails CI.
#
# Fixed so far (removed from this list):
#   - TaskResponse (Phase 0.7 PR2 Class D, 2026-04-16) —
#     backend mapTask emitted `createdByStaffName`/`assignedToStaffName`
#     but frontend consumers read `createdByName`/`assignedToName` →
#     task cards silently rendered undefined for months. Fixed by
#     aligning backend response field names to what frontend reads.
#     See taskService.ts mapTask() + docs/fix-registry.md TYPEDUP:TaskResponse.
#
# Remaining 46 duplicates — each one needs the same investigation.
# Tracked as Phase 0.7 PR3 (follow-up from PR2).

